                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002 Manchuria/180: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1" type="to"
                            >Johnson</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-08T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 8, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>201. Your 748, June 30, 2 p.m.</p>
                <p>1. Department suggests that such requests for instruction be accompanied by
                    indication of Legation’s views.</p>
                <p>2. Department regards as appropriate the reply made by you as reported in last
                    paragraph, first sentence.</p>
                <p>Department desires that you refrain from making further reply, unless your
                    Japanese colleague again approaches you on the subject. In that event, only,
                    Department suggests that you should reply briefly in the same terms.</p>
                <p>3. Do you regard the statement reported in penultimate paragraph of your telegram
                    under reference as a serious threat and likely to be carried out?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
